Checking the nature of the residuals ( Checking the normality assumptions)

co2.residuals = resid(co2.linear.model)
hist(co2.residuals, main='Histograms of residuals')

# in case of the few datapoints, histograms is not the right way to check the normality of the residuals. We can use Normal Q-Q plot.
qqnorm(co2.residuals)
qqline(co2.residuals)

# Plot the residuals vs independent variable
plot(co2.residuals~time(co2))

plot(co2.residuals~time(co2),xlim=c(1960,1963),main='Zoomed Residuals')

plot(extra~group,data=sleep,main='Extra Sleep in Gossett Data by Group')

attach(sleep)
extra.1 = extra[group==1]
extra.2 = extra[group==2]
# testing the hypothesis that effect of group 1 is same as group2.

t.test(extra.1,extra.2,paired=TRUE,alternative = 'two.sided')

Week 2 : Time plots using the package astsa.

data used : jj <— Johnson and Johnson Quarterly Earning per share. : flu <— Monthly pneumonia and influenza deaths in the U.S., 1968 to 1978 :globtemp <— Global mean land-ocean temperature deviations :globtempl <— Global mean land (only) temperature deviations :star <— magnitude of a star taken at midnight for 600 consecutive days

require(astsa)
## Loading required package: astsa
## Warning: package 'astsa' was built under R version 3.4.3
plot(jj, type='o', main='Johnson and Johnson Quarterly Earning per share',
     xlab='Years', ylab='Earnings')

plot(flu, main='Monthly pneumonia and influenza deaths in US', xlab='Years', ylab='Number of Deaths per 10,000 people')

plot(globtemp, main='Global mean land-ocean temperature deviations' , xlab='Years', ylab='Temperature Deviations in Centigrade')

plot(globtempl, type='o', main='Global mean land (only) temperature deviations', xlab='Years', ylab='Land Temperature Deviations')

plot(star, main='magnitude of a star taken at midnight for 600 consecutive days', xlab='Days', ylab='Magnitude')

Random Walk

x=NULL
x[1] = 0
for (i in 2:1000){ 
  x[i] = x[i-1] + rnorm(1)
}
random_walk = ts(x)
plot(random_walk, main='Random Walk' , xlab='Days', col='blue' , lwd=2)

# Differencing is the method to remove trend in the series.

Modelling Moving Average Process

# Generate noise
noise=rnorm(10000)

# Introduce a variable
ma_2=NULL

# Loop for generating MA(2) process

for(i in 3:10000){
    ma_2[i]=noise[i]+0.7*noise[i-1]+0.2*noise[i-2]
}

# Shift data to left by 2 units
moving_average_process=ma_2[3:10000]

# Put time series structure on a vanilla data
moving_average_process=ts(moving_average_process)

# Partition output graphics as a multi frame of 2 rows and 1 column
par(mfrow=c(2,1))

# plot the process and plot its ACF
plot(moving_average_process, main='A moving average process of order 2', ylab=' ', col='blue')
acf(moving_average_process, main='Correlogram of a moving average process of order 2')
